WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.440
but I really wanted to do this topic. I changed the title because I think

00:00:03.440 --> 00:00:07.640
this conference and all the conferences I've been to in the last, you know, three, six months,

00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:12.940
yes, there are toxicities. We are messing people's immune systems up, right? Amazing responses,

00:00:13.160 --> 00:00:17.360
bispecifics, CAR Ts, but thinking about all the rheumatological things we learned in the past,

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:20.880
sometimes these T cells are going to do things that we don't know about. And it's really important

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:25.040
to figure that out and then learn how to actually treat those patients and then eventually prevent

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:29.400
it so that we can use these amazing therapies for our patients. So again, I still start with

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:33.740
this is the reason I didn't quit during COVID and I didn't go to pharma because my patients

00:00:33.740 --> 00:00:38.080
did so well on a therapy that I thought these patients were going to die. I didn't know that

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:42.540
they were going to actually live for years, five years for some patients. They actually respond

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:47.000
to treatments after CAR-T therapy, even when they're relapsing. The majority of my patients,

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:51.020
when they relapse from CAR-T, even if they don't make it to five years, I have options for other

00:00:51.020 --> 00:00:55.040
lines of therapy. We heard a little bit about lymphoma where after bispecifics, it's harder

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:59.040
to treat those patients, especially if they're on continuous dosing. So I wanted to say,

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:03.640
I still think CAR-T is really, really important. And I still offer it to most of my patients in

00:01:03.640 --> 00:01:07.980
second line. Again, I get I'm in a bubble and I have access to all these things, but most of my

00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:12.160
patients, even standard dress, because of those outcomes, we'll go to second line CAR-T. And I

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:16.640
think that's the big message here, that everything is an evolution, right? So yes, the delayed

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:22.800
neurotoxicity that we saw with CARTATUDE1, 6%. And again, there's been a lot of work done at Mount

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:28.000
Sinai and lots of other places that have really looked at this. I will say in my standard of care

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:29.380
practice, I actually have done a lot of work on CARTATUDE1. I've done a lot of work on CARTATUDE2.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:33.880
Zero patients out of 190 we've treated now that have gotten Guillain-Barre or Parkinson's.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:38.340
Again, I'm going to talk about why I think that is, but really we've learned this and this really

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:43.140
changes that outcome. And again, even in CARTATUDE4, it was a 0.51 patient that had Parkinson's,

00:01:43.180 --> 00:01:47.700
right? So really important to know these things and figure out how to fix it and prevent it and

00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:52.880
treat it if it does happen. But again, it changes from two, three years ago to what it is today.

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:57.460
And same thing with IEC colitis. Some of our patients have had some serious IEC colitis,

00:01:57.460 --> 00:01:59.380
and that's what I'm going to share in a little bit.

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:03.300
So again, I'm not going to read most of my slides. It's there for you to look at later,

00:02:03.460 --> 00:02:08.000
but really there are some mechanisms as why we think maybe the neurotoxicity happens. I do think

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.700
the neurotox versus the IEC colitis are probably a little different. There are some patients that

00:02:12.700 --> 00:02:19.000
can get both, but again, important. CLOUDIN9, the reason I brought this up, all of these things are

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.480
multifactorial. I will say that yes, there is a target called CLOUDIN9 that is something that

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:29.360
all of us have on neural tissues normally expressed in studies. We don't know that the

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:35.900
actually plays a role in any of the neurotoxicity that happens in either the MNTs or the

00:02:35.900 --> 00:02:40.980
Parkinsonianism type. But in the lab, we can see that if there's increased CLOUDIN9, that there

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:45.120
are certain CAR-Ts that attach to that and others don't. So again, it's a hypothesis. It does not

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:49.280
mean it's the main cause, but really important to know because again, if it was not increased

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:54.820
expression, then why are these patients getting it? Not everybody. And I think again, some of it

00:02:54.820 --> 00:02:58.360
has to do with the expansion of the CAR-Ts. We've talked about ALC. I'm going to come to that in a

00:02:58.360 --> 00:02:58.640
second.

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:04.500
Versus is there also a role for a particular antigen? We don't know. And so in terms of

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:08.760
diagnosis and clinical features, I'm not going to go into it. But again, MNTs versus Parkinsonianism,

00:03:08.760 --> 00:03:12.880
they are a little bit different. Most of these patients, usually a month after is where we start

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:17.580
seeing a day 28, 20, 30 or later, and usually in the first three to six months. So to most of my

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:21.280
patients, I tell them if three to six months, you're doing great. I'm actually not worried

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:24.980
too much about you. I have a few patients that even a year or two years later, they might have

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:29.160
personality changes and we do something to figure that out. But again, the majority of

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:33.600
patients, once they're out three to six months, things look really exciting and then I don't see

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:39.540
them, but every three months. And so the biggest thing I will say is that prevention strategies,

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:44.880
I think the effect of bridging. Again, CARTITUDE 1 versus CARTITUDE 4, we saw that patients who got

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:50.760
better bridging had a much lower risk of all of these toxicities, especially Parkinsonianism.

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:56.340
Cranial nerve palsies, maybe not. Again, I haven't seen as many in our earlier line patients now,

00:03:56.340 --> 00:03:59.340
which I don't know exactly why. But in the late line patients,

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:03.240
even with great bridging, we would see some of these cranial nerve palsies. So we would just

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:07.440
pick up on them really fast, treat them, and most of those patients turned around within a week or

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:13.980
two. The Parkinson's, again, much lower risk when you actually improve bridging. So the question is,

00:04:13.980 --> 00:04:18.780
is it expansion or are there other things? Now, of course, the ALC, we came up with this argument

00:04:18.780 --> 00:04:23.340
yesterday too, that there are some centers that will treat an ALC of three to five with steroids,

00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:28.680
other centers like Mayo that will actually maybe even give Cytoxan. And our center doesn't give

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:29.360
anything unless they have something to do with it. But there are centers that will actually maybe even

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:29.360
give Cytoxan. And our center doesn't give anything unless they have something to do with it.

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:29.360
And our center doesn't give anything unless they have something to do with it.

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:33.740
And so again, I think everything's evolving so much that some of these differences we're seeing

00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:37.780
could just be that we're getting better at treating our patients, and especially earlier

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:44.920
line. Okay. And then the only other thing I wanted to bring up for standard of care is, remember,

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:50.820
in trials, patients cannot, they have washout windows, we have to wait. We only give certain

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:54.620
kinds of bridging sometimes. Where in the real world, I am free to do so many other things. So

00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:59.180
I will say it is harder for me to treat a patient on a clinical trial, even though those patients are

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:03.760
eligible for trials, than treating a patient for standard of care CAR-T that isn't eligible for a

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:08.580
trial. So the logistics make a huge difference in what I can and can't do. So with IUC colitis,

00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:14.100
most of this data is from Mark Hamilton and Lekha Milkaneni from our consortium, as well as MD

00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:18.560
Anderson data that I'm showing you here. And again, this does seem to be, these papers have

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:22.660
been submitted, so I don't have pictures. I have some of the data from their posters from ASTCT.

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:27.580
But really, it does seem to be that the patients who get this, it seems to be a lymphoproliferative

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:29.280
disorder and not necessarily gynecological. And so I think it's really important that we

00:05:29.280 --> 00:05:34.860
make sure that we're not just a immune-mediated enterocolitis. There are certain cell types that

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:39.600
we're seeing. We do see clonal CAR-T expansion, but they are not just TET2 or some of the things

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:45.040
that Gurbaksh talked about earlier. There's other clones that we're seeing that we don't know exactly

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:49.020
what to make of. What's interesting, this is not colitis, this is enterocolitis. So what makes it

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:53.520
easier to diagnose now is that for most of our patients, the second they have major symptoms, we

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:57.540
actually do an EGD. So I don't have to worry about cleaning out their colons, et cetera, and I can get

00:05:57.540 --> 00:05:59.240
it done really quickly.

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:05.420
The incidence, 5.1% for our patients when we had up to 158 patients. Thankfully, getting up to 190

00:06:05.420 --> 00:06:10.580
or so now, we haven't had another case. So we'll see. But again, really important to monitor for

00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:15.360
this. And so what we see here, I'm going to talk about the key diagnostic thresholds. What we

00:06:15.360 --> 00:06:19.980
figured out from the nine patients that we had, these were patients that at day 28, 30, when we

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:24.040
checked their CAR-T expansion, because we can follow that at MD Anderson, if they were 100

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:29.200
cells per microliter at day 28 or 30, they had a higher risk. Not everybody gets it, but they had a

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:33.760
much higher risk than any of the patients that had less. Our T's go up, but they come down. But if

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:38.820
they stay high, then we worry. And then we have a test with that pathology. When we do that EGD, we

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:43.240
can actually look for camelid. And we decided that if it was 20% or more, we'd go ahead and call it

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:48.160
IEC colitis and treat it. And then even if you have low inflammatory markers, you don't see anything

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:53.740
on imaging, this still could be IEC colitis. And again, intervening early is what helps. So I'm

00:06:53.740 --> 00:06:59.160
going to quickly just say for our patients, this is our pathway we have right now. It's evolving. If we

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:03.180
treat a patient with IEC colitis, they can have infections at the same time. You treat the

00:07:03.180 --> 00:07:07.200
infection two, three days later, they're not getting better. We get the EGD. We see this

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:12.780
diagnostic on path. This is the pathway for treatment. If their PS is zero to two, they don't

00:07:12.780 --> 00:07:17.460
have serious infections issues, we try to kill the T cells. So that's usually with Cytoxan-based

00:07:17.460 --> 00:07:23.460
therapy followed by rexalitinib and VEDO. So when these patients have leaders of diarrhea, things

00:07:23.460 --> 00:07:27.420
like rexalitinib, they can't actually absorb it. We actually see the pills come out. So we use it

00:07:27.420 --> 00:07:29.120
as maintenance after, but really

00:07:29.120 --> 00:07:33.600
the T cells, most of our patients resolved within one to two weeks. And then we were able to do some

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:36.900
type of maintenance. With patients who are a little bit more frail, we've actually gotten

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:42.180
some responses with cyclosporine or tacrolimus. It's a little bit harder. We do IV first again,

00:07:42.180 --> 00:07:46.860
because they can't absorb, but eventually we go to a maintenance there. And so with that,

00:07:46.940 --> 00:07:49.540
I'm just going to come back here again. You'll have all the slides and some of the

00:07:49.540 --> 00:07:54.560
other data that's in there, but really I think this is one of the best therapies we've seen,

00:07:54.680 --> 00:07:57.940
especially the one in Dunn. Our patients feel great. I have patients that go back to work.

00:07:58.360 --> 00:07:58.960
It's really big.

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:02.800
So I think the goal is not to fear these toxicities. It's really to recognize them,

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:05.700
act swiftly and figure out how we can prevent them in the future.
